### Dynamic Track Switching (DTS) for MOQT Relays
Will Law presented on Dynamic Track Switching (DTS) for MOQT Relays, outlining the progress of the proposal:
* **Timeline & Progress:** 
  * Initially proposed in Boulder.
  * Design team established a draft.
  * Cisco developed a Proof of Concept (POC) demoed by Suhas Nandakumar.
  * Presented at IETF Shenzhen.
  * Consensus to adopt was reached at the May 11 virtual interim.
  * Nokia developed an implementation, leading to the current open PR #1638.

* **Nokia Implementation Demo:** Will Law shared a pre-recorded demo prepared by Yu You (Nokia) showcasing DTS in action:
  * The setup utilized three media tracks within a set (500 kbps, 1500 kbps, and 3000 kbps). 
  * The relay received all three tracks but only forwarded a single track.
  * The demonstration showed smooth, continuous switching by toggling the forward state.
  * When switching was disabled, the receiver maintained the 1080p feed regardless of bitrate input variations.
  * Under simulated highly aggressive throughput oscillations, the system successfully managed fast-frequency switching close to segment boundaries.

* **PR #1638 Design Changes:** 
  * Will Law highlighted a recent change to the PR regarding how switching is activated. 
  * Previously, "activate switching" was a binary flag sent with the registration of the last track. However, because out-of-order delivery of track registrations cannot be prevented in transport, the arrival order of tracks is not guaranteed. 
  * Consequently, the binary flag approach has been revised to avoid inadvertently triggering switching before all tracks in the set are available.
  * There are five remaining open issues on PR #1638 that the WG needs to resolve to integrate DTS into the main specifications.

